Alumni Home About Us Alumni Alumni members have borrowing privileges and off-campus access to a limited range of e-resources. WSU Community hours access is available to registered Alumni on presentation of a current GradLife card and photo ID. A requirement of Alumni Library membership is registering with the Alumni Team, Please email alumni@westernsydney.edu.au or register online to obtain a GradLife card. Once GradLife registration is complete, activate your Alumni Library membership by completing our Library membership form . Alumni members who have registered with the Office of Employability and Graduate Success and have not yet received their GradLife card, are still able to borrow from the Library upon presentation of photo identification. Alumni may continue to use their existing Western ID card if it’s not a GradLife card. Alumni e-resources Alumni loan conditions Library membership does not include Document Delivery, borrowing Reserve Collection material, or access to the Library's electronic resources unless otherwise specified. Study Smart Referencing & Citation Academic Integrity Module (AIM) Subject Guides eResources Contact Us As students and staff at the Western Sydney University, Indonesia Surabaya campus, you have access to the extensive resources and services provided by the local Surabaya campus library and our online resources and support. The keys to getting started are below. Explore the menu options to discover more about how the Library can help you succeed in your studies. Opening Hours
Display of Opening hours « Previous Next » Aug 18 Monday Aug 19 Tuesday Aug 20 Wednesday Aug 21 Thursday Aug 22 Friday Aug 23 Saturday Aug 24 Sunday

Indonesia - Surabaya 8:30am – 5pm 8:30am – 5pm 8:30am – 5pm 8:30am – 5pm 8:30am – 5pm Closed Closed Activities, Events & Talks Check out our lively program of online events, activities and thought-provoking talks. Note: AEST Borrowing General Collection All General Collection items are loaned for 14 days. You will need to either renew them or bring them back to the Library. Items on loan must be returned before or on the due date to avoid penalties. See Managing Your Loans & Requests for further details. Online Collections Online material loan periods are displayed at the time of borrowing and are set by the vendor. Membership & Conditions Of Use Students Eligibility : Currently enrolled Western Sydney University Indonesia (Surabaya) students Students can have 5 General Collection items on loan at any one time Request General Collection items access most e-resources off-campus Staff Eligibility : Current Western Sydney University Indonesia (Surabaya) staff Staff can have 5 General Collection items on loan at any one time request General Collection items access most e-resources from off-campus loan one print journal for three days. Journals must be returned on the due date. How To Use The Library Getting Started The Library has a range of resources available for loan. You will require a Library card to loan physical resources from the library. Your ID card is your Library card. Familiarise yourself with your Conditions of Use You are responsible for all transactions on your record in the Library system. Lost cards should be reported to the library to ensure no unauthorised use. You are responsible for the timely return of borrowed items irrespective of the receipt or non-receipt of email notices. Requesting If local Surabaya campus item you need is already on loan you may place a request on the item to be made available for you when it is returned. Request items via the Library Search Box 'Request' link. There is no charge for this service. A courtesy availability email will be sent to your email account once the item is ready to collect. Items will be held for seven (7) days at the nominated pickup location. Requests cannot be placed by clients with overdue items and/or fees of $10 or greater. Managing Your Loans & Requests You can login to My Library to: Review items on loan and see their due dates Renew your loans View the status of requested items Review any outstanding fees General Collection items may be renewed three times, for a total loan period of 8 weeks. Items that have been requested by others will not be renewable and the item must be returned by the due date. You will need to return items to the Library on level 35. Failure to return items will result in them being marked as Lost and a $125 replacement charge will be applied. Amounts of $10 or greater must be paid in full to restore borrowing privileges. Courtesy notices are sent to your email account to alert you to: Library items due for return Requested items available for collection Lost items and associated fees Please check your email account regularly to take full advantage of this service. Membership & Borrowing Home About Us Membership & Borrowing Collections Condition Of Use See Blocks, Charges & Holds and Collection Access Policy for further details. General Collection Standard Loans apply to all General collection items. With the following exceptions, all Standard loan items are automatically renewed every 14 days up to a maximum of 365 days, or to the end of the membership period, upon which date they must be returned to the Library: Item has been requested by another library member Item is overdue Client has other overdue items Client has a Library Hold on their University Student record Client does not have a current membership Standard loan items can be borrowed from and returned to any Western Sydney University campus library. Members can request Standard loan items to be delivered between campuses for pick up. Online Collections Online Online material loan periods are displayed at the time of borrowing and are set by the vendor. Reserve Collection Only current Western Sydney University student and staff library members are eligible to borrow Reserve collection items. As Reserve collection items are by nature in high demand, they are subject to shorter lending periods and higher penalties for late return. Reserve collection loan periods are 1 day and are not automatically renewed. They must be returned to the campus library from which they were borrowed by the end of the initial borrowing period. Only two Reserve collection items can be borrowed at any time. Print Journal Articles Western students and staff may request copies of articles held in print journals, and held only at a campus library other than your home library. These articles are scanned and emailed to your Western email account. To request an article from another campus library: Check item is available via the Library search box Send the complete citation for the required article to libicjr@westernsydney.edu.au . Be sure to include the journal title, volume/issue number, year of publication, article title and author and the page numbers if available Please allow two working days for delivery of item via your Western email. How To Use The Library Getting Started The Library has a wide range of resources available for loan. You will require a Library card to loan physical resources at the campus libraries. For Western students and staff , your ID card is your Library card. For Alumni Members, your GradLife card is your Library card. For all other membership types, the library will provide a Library card at the time of joining. Familiarise yourself with the loan conditions . Library items may be borrowed from and returned to any of the campus libraries . Return chutes are located within or near each library entrance. Wherever possible, items should be borrowed and returned using the Self-Service Machine located within the campus library. You are responsible for all transactions on your record in the Library system. Lost cards should be reported to the Library to ensure no unauthorised use. You are responsible for the timely return of borrowed items irrespective of the receipt or non-receipt of email notices. Please see Managing Your Loans and Requests for further information. Requesting & Intercampus Delivery If the item you need is unavailable at your "home" library, you may visit the campus library which has a copy available and borrow the item. Alternatively, you may request an item to be delivered via the Intercampus Delivery service for pick up at a nominated campus library. There is no charge for this service. Note : the courier service is not available to or from Sydney City Campus. Most items are available for Intercampus delivery, with the following exceptions: Reserve Collection material Not for loan materials Special collections Items may be requested via the Library Search Box 'Request' link. A courtesy availability email will be sent to your email account once the item is ready to collect. Items will be held for seven (7) days at the nominated pickup location. Requests cannot be placed by clients with overdue items and/or fees of $10 or greater. If available at the time of request, items will be delivered to the nominated library within three working days via the Intercampus Delivery service. View a demonstration for placing a request. Managing Your Loans & Requests You can login to My Library to: Review items on loan and see their due dates View the status of requested items Review any outstanding fees Items on loan are automatically renewed unless they’ve been requested, reached the 365-day loan limit, or are overdue. In these cases, you will need to bring them back to the Library. Items that are not returned will be marked as Lost and a $125 charge will be applied. Amounts of $10 or greater must be paid in full to restore borrowing privileges. Courtesy notices are sent to your email account to alert you to: Library items due for return Requested items available for collection Lost items and associated fees Please check your email account regularly to take full advantage of this service. How To Return Items With the exception of Reserve Collection material, items may be returned to any Western Sydney University Library . Returns chutes are located near each Library entrance. Items may also be returned via the Self-Service Machines located inside each Library. Reserve Collection material must be returned to the lending library and handed to a staff member at the Service Desk. Items may also be returned via Australia Post. These will be deemed returned on the day they are received by the library, not date of mailing. Mail returns to: Western Sydney University Library Locked Bag 1797 Penrith, NSW, 2751 Recalled Items Sometimes it may be necessary for the Library to recall material on loan. This will usually happen if the material is in high demand and required for the Reserve Collection. Recalled items have a shortened loan period of seven days from the date of recall or the original due date whichever falls first. Members Conditions Of Use & Registration Undergraduate Students Eligibility : Current Western Sydney University students enrolled in Bachelor's degrees (including those requiring graduate entry). Current Western Sydney University The College students and all non-award programs offered by the University. Current students enrolled in a university program taught by a Third Party Provider on behalf of the University. Undergraduate students can have 50 items on loan at any one time Standard loan items are automatically renewed every 14 days up to a maximum of 365 days, unless required to be returned sooner, upon which date they must be returned to the Library borrow and return to any Western Sydney University campus library (excluding Reserve collection items which must be returned to the lending campus library) Request General collection items to be delivered between campuses for pick up access most e-resources off-campus access the Library during WSU Community Hours, check current WSU Community Hours . See Collection Access Policy for further details. Postgraduate Students Eligibility : Western Sydney University students currently enrolled in Graduate Certificate, Graduate Diploma, Undergraduate Honours, Masters and Doctoral degrees offered by the University. Postgraduate students can have an unlimited number of items on loan at any one time Standard loan items are automatically renewed every 14 days up to a maximum of 365 days, unless required to be returned sooner, upon which date they must be returned to the Library borrow and return to any Western Sydney University campus library (excluding Reserve collection items which must be returned to the lending campus library) Request General collection items to be delivered between campuses for pick up access most e-resources from off-campus request items not held at Western Sydney University Library access the Library during WSU Community Hours, check current WSU Community Hours . See Collection Access Policy and Document Delivery Service for further details. Staff Eligibility : All current fulltime and part time Western Sydney University staff including: University Board of Trustees – All non-staff members of the University's Board of Trustees University Honorary Appointments - All persons currently in University Honorary Appointments Staff teaching under Third Party Provider (TPP) agreements, including educational designers Note: Staff, including TPP staff, are not eligible for Distance services. Additionally, TPP staff are not eligible for Document Delivery. Staff can have an unlimited number of items on loan at any one time Standard loan items are automatically renewed every 14 days up to a maximum of 365 days, unless required to be returned sooner, upon which date they must be returned to the Library borrow and return to any Western Sydney University campus library (excluding Reserve collection items which must be returned to the lending campus library) Request General collection items to be delivered between campuses for pick up access most e-resources from off-campus request items not held at Western Sydney University Library (excluding TPP staff) access the Library during WSU Community Hours, check current WSU Community Hours . See Collection Access Policy and Document Delivery Service for further details. Access Students Eligibility: Current Western Sydney University students registered with Disabilities Adviser. Access students can have 50 items on loan at any one time have an extended loan period of 84 days have additional services as agreed with Adviser borrow and return to any Western Sydney University campus library (excluding Reserve collection items which must be returned to the lending campus library) Request General collection items to be delivered between campuses for pick up access most e-resources off-campus access the Library during WSU Community Hours, check current WSU Community Hours . See Collection Access Policy for further details. Distance Students Eligibility: All currently enrolled Western Sydney University and Western Sydney University The College students with an Australian semester residential address located outside the Sydney metropolitan area. Distance Services excludes the following Sydney metropolitan area postcodes ranges of 1000 - 1920, 2000 - 2249, 2500 - 2574, 2740 – 2786. Distance Students can have 50 items on loan at any one time have an extended loan period of 84 days request a maximum of ten items per week to be posted to them. access most e-resources off-campus access the Library during WSU Community Hours, check current WSU Community Hours . See Collection Access Policy and Distance Services for further details. 1717 Students All current students enrolled in program 1717. 1717 students can have 50 items on loan at any one time have extended loan period of 84 days access most e-resources off-campus access the Library during WSU Community Hours, check current WSU Community Hours . See Collection Access Policy and Distance Services for further details. Alumni Members Eligibility: Western Sydney University graduates registered with GradLife. Alumni can have 50 Standard loan items on loan at any one time Standard loan items are automatically renewed every 14 days up to a maximum of 365 days, unless required to be returned sooner, upon which date they must be returned to the Library borrow and return to any Western Sydney University campus library Request General collection items to be delivered between campuses for pick up access a limited range of off-campus eResources access the Library during WSU Community Hours, check current WSU Community Hours . See Collection Access Policy and Alumni for further details. Reciprocal Members Eligibility: Any current student or staff eligible under ULANZ , or other reciprocal agreements to which the University Library is a party. Note: Annual membership and borrowing privileges expire February 28 each year. ULANZ is a borrowing agreement only and members will have access to Western's physical collections. It does not include Document Delivery, off-campus access to eResources or access to Study Hall. Infringements at Western Sydney University libraries may result in sanctions at the borrower's home library. For more information, contact the Library . Reciprocal members can have 20 Standard loan items on loan at any one time Standard loan items are automatically renewed every 14 days up to a maximum of 365 days, unless required to be returned sooner, upon which date they must be returned to the Library borrow and return to any Western Sydney University campus library Request General collection items to be delivered between campuses for pick up access Wi-Fi via EduROAM . How to Register : Complete an online registration form Visit a campus library with photo ID and proof of enrolment or employment from your home institution. Please allow one working day for processing. See Collection Access Policy for further details. Community Members Eligibility : Members of the public, learners in a Western Sydney University micro credential course, and Western Sydney University industry placement providers. Community membership is a borrowing agreement only and members will have access to our general physical collections. It does not include borrowing of Reserve Collection, off-campus access to eResources or Document Delivery. Membership is valid for 12 months from the date of joining. A new application is required each year. Note: individuals under 18 years of age require written parental/guardian authorisation. Community members can have 20 Standard loan items on loan at any one time Standard loan items are automatically renewed every 14 days up to a maximum of 365 days, unless required to be returned sooner, upon which date they must be returned to the Library borrow and return to any Western Sydney University campus library Request General collection items to be delivered between campuses for pick up. How to Register : Complete an online registration form Visit a campus library with photo ID. Please allow one working day for processing. See Collection Access Policy for further details. Corporate Members Eligibility: Companies interested in corporate borrowing may register their interest via our online form . This membership is subject to approval by the Executive Director of Library Services and fees may apply. Annual membership expires 12 months from date of registration. It does not include off campus access to eResources. Corporate members can have 20 Standard loan items on loan at any one time Standard loan items are automatically renewed every 14 days up to a maximum of 365 days, unless required to be returned sooner, upon which date they must be returned to the Library borrow and return to any Western Sydney University campus library Request General collection items to be delivered between campuses for pick up. See Collection Access Policy for further details. Blocks, Charges and Holds Home About Us Membership & Borrowing Blocks, Charges and Holds To avoid blocks and charges, members are encouraged to manage their library loans and to return items on time. Keep track of your borrowed items via My Library or Contact Us . Blocks If you have items that are overdue you will be blocked from borrowing or renewing your items until they are returned, and any related charges are paid. Lost items As outlined in the table below, items that are not returned will be marked as Lost and a $125 charge will be applied.

28 days after the due date item is considered Lost. $125 charge may be waived in exceptional circumstances if the item is returned within 55 days of due date For students: if not returned within 56 days a Hold may be placed on your Student Record leading to the withholding of examination results, academic transcripts and graduation until items are returned and/or outstanding lost item charges are paid in full. 24 hours after the due date item is considered Lost $125 charge may be waived when the item is returned For students: if not returned within 7 days a Hold may be placed on your Student Record leading to the withholding of examination results, academic transcripts and graduation until items are returned and/or outstanding lost item charges are paid in full. Contact our Online Librarians to discuss replacement of a lost item or waiving of charges due illness or misadventure. Damaged items If an item is returned damaged a $125 charge is applied. This amount may vary depending on the replacement cost of the item. Providing a physical replacement copy of lost or damaged items, instead of the $125 charge, will be considered on a case by case basis. Any replacement must be an identical copy in good condition of same or newer edition. Replacing a missing or damaged item incurs a non- refundable $25 processing charge. Contact our Online Librarians to discuss replacement of a damaged item or waiving of charges due illness or misadventure. See the Collection Access Policy for more details. LIBRARY NOTICES Library notices are sent as a courtesy only. At all times, clients are responsible for the timely return of borrowed items irrespective of the receipt/non-receipt of notices. You can always check your due dates in MyLibrary Due Date Notification email. Sent when item reaches due date and cannot be renewed Monthly Borrowing Statements are sent on the 2 nd of every month Lost loan item notifications are sent 28 days after the due date for standard items and 7 days for Reserve collection items. Requested item available notices are sent when the item is at the nominated pickup location. PAYMENTS Payment is made via OneStop . OneStop is a secure online credit card payment service. Processed by the Library the next working day. A printed copy of the receipt will be required if you wish to have your library record cleared immediately, or if payments are queried at a later date. When paying Library charges, please ensure that you do not pay more than the total amount owing. No refunds are provided for over-payment. Code of Conduct Home About Us Rules & Policies Code of Conduct The University Library serves the Western Sydney University community by providing high quality services and collections and a pleasant environment that is conducive to study and research. All Library clients are required to abide by the Library Rules . CONTRIBUTE TO A PLEASANT STUDY ENVIRONMENT BY: Ensuring all permitted food and drinks have appropriate lids/covers Placing all rubbish in the bins provided Returning all materials to designated areas within the Library REFRAIN FROM THE FOLLOWING ACTIVITIES: Any disturbance which disrupts research or study or interferes with normal use of the library: Noise, rowdiness and disruptive or offensive behaviour or language Conversation in Silent study areas or other areas as signposted Harassment of other clients or Library staff Use of mobile phones which have not been switched to silent/vibrate or use in speaker mode Use of mobile phones in Silent study areas Smoking, vaping, using e-cigarettes or alcohol consumption Improper use of Library facilities and/or resources: Use of Library computing facilities for purposes not related to research or study, including access to inappropriate web sites and gaming Deliberate damage, defacement, mutilation, removal or attempted removal of Library materials or property Clients are required to comply with Western Sydney University Policies including the Student Misconduct Rule , and with State and Federal legislation. Failure to observe this Code of Conduct may lead to exclusion and possible withdrawal of Library privileges. Copyright Guidance Home About Us Rules & Policies Copyright Guidance The Statutory Licence for Works and Broadcasts COPYRIGHT ACT 1968 - Section 113P Copying and communicating works and broadcasts allows universities to copy and communicate works and broadcasts for educational and teaching purposes without seeking direct permission, provided that: The university pays an agreed remuneration negotiated by Universities Australia and the Copyright Agency for works and to Screenrights for broadcasts. Proper attribution is maintained. The material is shared only with enrolled students who need it for their subjects. The copied and communicated material does not unreasonably prejudice the legitimate interests of the copyright owner. The copying or communicating complies with any relevant agreement between the collecting society, Copyright Agency, Screenrights, and Universities Australia, representing Australian universities, or: The copying and communication meet the requirements outlined in a determination made by the Copyright Tribunal. Section 113P Copyright Notice: The copying and communication of works and broadcasts for educational and teaching purposes of the University requires the placement of the Section 113P Copyright Notice in front of all copied and communicated third-party copyright materials. For further information regarding the Section 113P Copyright Notice, don't hesitate to contact the University Copyright Officer via the WesternNow Form Copyright Advice . Music Licence for Universities The UNIVERSITIES MUSIC LICENCE was negotiated between the Australasian Performing Right Association, the Australasian Mechanical Copyright Owners Society, the Phonographic Performance Company of Australia, the Australian Recording Industry Association, and Universities Australia on behalf of the Universities Mentioned in Schedule A of the Remuneration Agreement, including Western Sydney University. The Universities Australia Factsheet provides information about The University Music Agreement . Music Licence for Universities summarises the activities enabled by the Licence. Always include the Music Copyright Notice when using sound recordings for educational purposes to ensure copyright compliance. For further information regarding Music Agreement for Universities, don't hesitate to contact the University Copyright Officer via the WesternNow Form Copyright Advice . WesternNow Forms to Use for Copyright Matters Copyright Advice This form is here to help with any copyright questions you might have regarding your educational, research, and teaching activities at Western Sydney University. Feel free to reach out if you need assistance! Copyright Infringement Notice Please use this form to report copyright infringement on the University’s network. Permission To Use Western Sydney University Copyright Material Please fill out this form to request permission to use Western Sydney University copyrighted material that an Open Access or Creative Commons Licence does not cover. Library Rules Home About Us Rules & Policies Library Rules GENERAL The University Library comprises libraries located at the Bankstown CIty , Campbelltown , Hawkesbury , Liverpool , Nirimba , Parramatta City , Parramatta South and Penrith campuses, thereinafter called the Library. The facilities of the Library are primarily for the use of current staff and students of Western Sydney University. Borrowing privileges may also be extended to members of the public or reciprocal borrowers. Non members may use the Library for research or study purposes provided they observe the Library Rules and conditions of use including the Library Code of Conduct . The Executive Director, Library may determine the services offered by the Library, and the users to whom these services may be provided. The Executive Director, Library (or authorised representative) has discretion to require a user to produce proof of identity or entitlement to use the Library. Blocks, charges and Holds outlined in the Library Collection Access Policy will apply to any breach of these Rules. Users must at all times act in accordance with instructions authorised by the Executive Director, Library and displayed on the Library website, in public areas, at service desks, computer terminals, photocopy and printing machines or in the Library's official publications. CONDITIONS OF USE OF THE LIBRARY All users of the Library have a right to pursue their study and research without unnecessary and/or unreasonable disturbance or distraction and have an obligation to respect the rights of others in accordance with the Library Code of Conduct . Mobile phones must be switched to silent/vibrate as users enter the Library, and not used in speaker mode. Food and drink brought into the Library must be in suitable covered containers to reduce spills. Noise, disturbance and unseemly behaviour are not permitted in the Library. Any person who does not observe the Library Rules and Library Code of Conduct may be excluded with possible withdrawal of Library privileges. Children under the age of twelve will not be admitted unless accompanied by and in the charge of an adult. Adults bringing children into the Library are responsible for their behaviour and for ensuring they do not disturb others. All users shall, on request of the Executive Director, Library or authorised representative, show their Western Sydney University ID card, Library Borrowers Card or other photo evidence of identity. Computing facilities are provided for research or study only. Users are responsible for ensuring that computing and communication facilities are used in an effective, efficient, ethical and lawful manner in compliance with the Acceptable Use of IT Resources policy. Users are reminded that it is a criminal offence, without authority or lawful excuse, to obtain access to a program or data, to destroy, erase, alter or insert data without authorization, or to intercept or obstruct the lawful use of a computer. Users must comply with the provisions of current Copyright legislation. Users are referred to the statutory notice posted adjacent to photocopying/printing/scanning machines. All books and the contents of bags and cases must be presented for inspection, on request from Library staff or when an electronic security alarm indicates that an item may have been incompletely loaned. Library student group study rooms may be booked by Western Sydney University students for the purposes of small group study, subject to the booking conditions on the Library website. These rooms are not available for meetings of clubs or societies, as tutorial spaces or as substitute classrooms for regularly scheduled lectures or classes. Breaches of these Rules will be treated in accordance with the Student Misconduct Rule . BORROWING Categories of material for borrowing All materials in the Western Sydney University Library's collections are normally available for loan with the exceptions listed below. The University Librarian, or her/his representative, may approve lending from the categories below in special circumstances: Serials, including newspapers, calendars, examination papers Items marked NOT FOR LOAN Reference items Microform items Higher degree theses Rare books, valuable books, and vulnerable items which are stored in closed access Items from the Reserve Collections which where the loan would be outside standard Reserve Collection access. BORROWING CONDITIONS - DEFINITIONS In these Rules: "ID Card" means either the official student or staff identification card issued by the University "Library Card" means the borrowing card issued by the Library to authorised external users "Inter-Library Loan" means an item borrowed from another library by the Western Sydney University Library on behalf of a user, which for the duration of the loan shall be treated as being a Western Sydney University Library item and be subject to the same Rules as Western Sydney University Library items "Patron Barcode" means a machine readable barcode which assigns to the user a unique identification number "Patron Record" means an official library system record which indicates the user's current registration and borrowing status. BORROWING PROCESS Users shall: Register with the Western Sydney University Library prior to borrowing if they are not a Western Sydney University student or staff member Present items for borrowing at the self-service machines or service desk together with their ID card or Library card. Other photo identification may be accepted at the service desk/s Report to Western Sydney University Library staff if items are damaged prior to borrowing; Return Western Sydney University Library materials via self-service machines or a designated return chute at any Western Sydney University campus library listed above, or via mail RESPONSIBILITY OF USERS Users shall be responsible for: Ensuing, before they leave the Western Sydney University Library, that any Library item that they remove from the premises of the Library has been registered as borrowed The safekeeping and return on or before the due date, as recorded in the library system, of items borrowed on their ID or Library card The safekeeping of their ID or Library card. Card holders are responsible for any transaction involving the use of their card. Users are responsible for all materials consulted, whether borrowed for use outside the Library or not, and will be held liable for any loss, mutilation or other damage. The full cost of either repair or replacement shall on demand be payable to the University, together with a service fee. RESTRICTIONS Unless authorised by the Executive Director, Library or her/his authorised representative users shall not: Be permitted to borrow without their ID or Library card; Lend their ID or Library card to any other person for the purposes of borrowing Library items or accessing online resources; Return materials from other libraries, with the exception of Inter-Library Loans, to Western Sydney University Library. RECIPROCAL BORROWING Where Western Sydney University Library has formal borrowing arrangements with other institutions, authorised members of such institutions may register for borrowing privileges at the Library provided they are: Either students currently enrolled in award courses of academic study, or current employees of the institution, and Are in good standing with the home institution RESERVE COLLECTION Only current members of Western Sydney University are eligible to use materials placed in Reserve Collections. BORROWING PRIVILEGES Borrowing privileges and loan periods will be as determined from time to time and so detailed on the Library website and in official Western Sydney University Library publications. The Executive Director, Library or her/his nominee may vary the loan period for any item, or may recall an item at any time. When an item is recalled, the date stipulated on the recall notice becomes the date due. PENALTIES AND FEES Failure to return a borrowed item on or before the due date or time, or failure to return a recalled item within one week of the request, will incur a late fee. The fee is payable on each overdue item at a rate approved by the Board of Trustees from time to time and advertised in the Library Borrowing Conditions. All borrowing and renewal privileges will be suspended pending return of overdue items and payment of late fees if fees total $10 or more. Such privileges will be reinstated when the debt is paid. Where material has been lost or returned damaged or not returned after a reasonable period, the user is required to pay the cost of repair or replacement of the material together with a service charge levied to cover the cost of administrative processes involved. The Executive Director, Library reserves the right to apply the actual replacement cost where the material to be replaced is of a value deemed to be well in excess of the standard fee. The Library Collection Access Policy provides a comprehensive statement of borrowing and associated Library activities. Using the Library Home About Us Using the Library Library hours and locations Opening hours vary dependent upon the time in the academic year and the individual library. Check your campus library page for hours, address, location maps and a virtual tour. WSU community hours operates at identified campus libraries and provides extended access after general Library hours cease. WSU Community hours vary, so, so check the opening hours for your campus. Entry to the Library during WSU Community hours requires a current Western ID or Gradlife card. Library Spaces Study Spaces The Library provides a variety of study spaces to suit the way you prefer to study. Each campus has shared, open study areas and student group study rooms for collaborative work, while quiet and silent spaces allow for focused study. Book a Student Group Study Room Bookable online by University students with a current WesternAccount, each campus library offers group study rooms for collaborating on projects, studying with other students and for practicing presentations. Book the trial BYOD recording space at Parramatta South. We are trialling a BYOD recording space for students to use to create content for your assessments. A recording studio equipment kit with microphone, adapter cables and mini mount is available to borrow from the service desk with your booking. Available from 8:30am - 5:00pm, Monday - Friday for up to 3 hours per booking, bookings are required . A recording studio equipment kit with adaptors can be borrowed from the service desk with your booking. Your feedback via this form will inform the final space design. Book a Library space Are you running a workshop, have a book to launch or a work that you would like to exhibit? Do you need space for a collaborative get-together? The Library has a number of different spaces that may suit. Contact your local Precinct Librarian to discuss opportunities to use Library spaces, or complete the Western Now form . Facilities Printing, photocopying and scanning. Printing, photocopying services at Western Sydney University campus libraries deliver high speed, quality copying, scanning and printing. Information on these services, operating procedures and associated equipment can be found in the copy/print areas or by asking at the Library Service Point. Parramatta City Campus printing and photocopying is provided by Campus Services. Free Wifi. Western WiFi is the University's on campus wireless network, provided free of charge to current students, staff, and some associates of the University. Using your WesternAccount to log in, students and staff on all campuses are able to access the Internet from smartphones, PDAs, iPhones, iPads, Android 4 (or later), Linux based devices, and more. Visit the ITDS webpage for more details. Sleep Pods on campus. Sleep Pods are available at Campbelltown, Hawkesbury, Liverpool, Parramatta South and Penrith campus libraries. All the features of the Sleep Pod are designed to help you relax - the zero gravity position, specially composed sleep music and gentle wake sequence of programmed lights and vibrations will have you rested and rejuvenated in no time. Try a nap next time you are on campus. Library etiquette The Library is a space for everyone to use, so consider others and act respectfully when using the Library. Be aware of the noise level limits in different areas of campus libraries like the silent study and quiet study zones. The university is a smoke-free and vape-free zone. The Library Code of Conduct outlines the behaviours from which clients are asked to refrain whilst within the Library. The Library rules supplement the Library Loans Policy and Code of Conduct for Library clients. For concerns about noise and behaviour, see staff at the campus service point, contact the Online Librarian or Campus Safety and Security . Student Group Study Rooms Home About Us Using the Library Student Group Study Rooms Book a room at: Bankstown City – via Resource Booker Campbelltown Hawkesbury Liverpool Parramatta City – via Resource Booker Parramatta South Penrith These rooms are bookable online by Western Sydney University students with a current WesternAccount. To maximise availability of rooms, the following conditions apply: A maximum of one booking per day, of up to two hours per student. Bookings may be made up to 2 weeks in advance. Study rooms are for student group study only, where a group consists of two or more people. Rooms cannot be booked for individual use. You can cancel your booking by clicking on the link provided in the confirmation email, and then clicking on the Cancel booking button. You forgo your booking if the booked room is not occupied within ten minutes of the booked start time. Please do not leave any items unattended. The Library accepts no responsibility for any personal items and reserves the right to ask security to remove unattended items. The Library reserves the right to cancel bookings in violation of these conditions. Book the trial BYOD recording space at Parramatta South. We are trialling a BYOD recording space for students to use to create content for your assessments. A recording studio equipment kit is available to borrow from the service desk with your booking. It includes: adapter cables a mini mount for your device a professional microphone Available from 8:30am - 5:00pm, Monday - Friday for up to 3 hours per booking, bookings are required . A recording studio equipment kit with adaptors can be borrowed from the service desk with your booking. Your feedback via this form will inform the final space design. Staff members wishing to book Library spaces should contact the Precinct Librarian to discuss opportunities. Printing, Photocopying and Scanning Home About Us Using the Library Printing, Photocopying and Scanning PrintFree is the print, copy and scan service for Western students and staff. Available at all campus libraries, you can: Print or copy in black & white or colour Choose A3 or A4 size paper Scan in black & white or colour and email it to yourself Print from your device using Wireless Printing You’ll need a current and activated Western Sydney University account. Then tap your ID card to use the machines. Need to know more? Visit the FAQs page . Not a Western student or staff member? Speak with library staff about how you can print, copy or scan. Remember. It is your responsibility to abide by the Copyright Act. A section of the act is displayed in each photocopying area Reporting A Problem Need help with PrintFree? Study Spaces Home About Us Using the Library Study Spaces The Library provides a variety of spaces for your use. Each area is designed to meet different study needs and requires different behaviours. Know Your Study Spaces

Open Study Areas Individuals up to medium-sized groups (1 – 8 people) for study purposes (see Library Code of Conduct ) Moderate noise not heard beyond your group. Phones on silent and not used in speaker mode. Covered food and drink. Please place rubbish in bins.

Student Group Study Rooms Small to medium sized groups (2 - 8 people) for study purposes (see Student Group Study Rooms and Library Code of Conduct ). Moderate noise not heard beyond your room. Bookings take preference over walk-in use. Phones on silent. Covered food and drink. Please place rubbish in bins. Quiet Study Areas Individuals up to small groups of 1 – 3 people. Quiet conversations only. Phones on silent and used in Open Study Areas. Covered food and drinks. Please place rubbish in bins. Silent Study Areas Individual study only. No food, covered drinks only. Phones on silent and used in Open Study Areas. Please move to another area for all conversations. Please place rubbish in bins. Access Rooms Specialised accessible seating, tables and other equipment.. Eligible students registered with the Disability Service. If you are not sure where the different spaces are located in your campus library ask at the Service Desk or contact the Online Librarian . WSU Community hours Home About Us Using the Library WSU Community hours The Library offers extended access at identified campus libraries to current Western students and staff and registered Alumni , at different times of the year, as WSU Community hours. WSU Community hours and dates will vary between campuses. See our Hours and Locations page for campus-specific information. Normal library rules regarding food and behaviour apply. During WSU Community hours, you will be able to: tap/swipe in using a valid Western Sydney University ID* card to access the library. If your card does not work, please see the Campus Safety and Security office There is a security guard on duty, no Library staff. use the self-service machines to borrow and return items from the main library collection; use the public desktop computers; use the printing, photocopying and scanning facilities. You will not be able to access assistance with equipment, staff areas or any courtyards. *Alumni members will need to attract the attention of the security guard and present their GradLife card together with photo ID. If you have any queries, please contact the Library . Feedback about this service is welcome. World - Dr Lynde Tan In today’s digital world
Campus, Peter Shergold Building, Level 9 Conference Room 2

Thought Leadership Panel: Climate Justice Through Reuse and Repair Join researchers, council representatives, activists, and community organisers for a dynamic conversation on how everyday practices of reuse and repair such as clothing swaps, mending, and circular sharing, can be harnessed for climate justice. This panel will explore how local action can drive broader systems change, build post-election climate momentum, and revalue care-based practices as legitimate climate strategies. Panellists: Dr Jenna Condie – Western Sydney University / Blue Mountains Parents for Climate Rob Morrison, Blue Mountains City Council representative – Local government climate & reuse strategy Nic Seton, CEO Parents for Climate – Community-based climate action Student activist – WSU Clothes swap organiser (tbc) (Chair/MC): A/Prof Stephen Healy, Western Sydney University Guiding questions: What is your current project and how does it connect reuse/repair with climate justice? How can researchers, councils, and communities collaborate to extend impact? What does an effective post-election climate politics look like from the ground up? How can reuse and repair practices be recognised as legitimate and measurable forms of climate action? Come along to be inspired, challenged, and connected. How Autobiography Helps Health Professionals Understand Women’s Experience of Postpartum Psychosis Dr Diana Jefferies is a senior lecturer in the School of Nursing and Midwifery at Western Sydney University. She has a clinical background in mental health and HIV/AIDS nursing and an academic background in the humanities. It is this interdisciplinary combination of knowledge that has sparked her interest in exploring how women make meaning of their mental distress after childbirth, their access to healthcare, their response to treatment, and any strategies they may use to promote recovery. One method of accessing how women make meaning of their experience of postpartum mental distress is through published autobiography. As this is the woman’s writing, unmediated by the health professional’s lens, their thoughts about their illness become a pure distillation of their experience. This experience can then be read against current clinical knowledge and guidelines to identify if gaps in services exist and could be improved from these personal accounts. Dr Jefferies will discuss three autobiographies of women’s accounts of postpartum psychosis, which occurs in 1-2 women in 1000 in the first four to six weeks following childbirth. This condition is a frightening and traumatic experience for the woman as she experiences rapid mood swings, hallucinations, delusions and confused thinking. Many women are reluctant to disclose their symptoms as they worry about losing custody of their child. Even though women may recognise there is something wrong, they may not receive treatment until the illness has become very severe. These autobiographies are: The Book of Margery Kempe (c.1400), Oxford University Press (2015) Thomas Walsh, Amanda (2022): A Mother’s Mind: A Story of Postnatal Psychosis, Anxiety and Depression, Green Olive Press. Beetson, Ariane (2024): Because I’m Not Myself: A Memoir of Motherhood, Madness and Coming Back from the Brink, Black Inc. Reading about women’s experience of postnatal psychosis from the early 15 th century to the present demonstrates a long view of an illness that remains constant. It is from this perspective that it can be read against current clinical guidelines to ensure that women have optimum health accounts. Reducing Inequalities through Financial Literacy - Associate Professor Michelle Cull When Associate Professor Michelle Cull began teaching a course at Western Sydney University on financial planning, she noticed that although students had a strong interest in basic personal finance, they lacked knowledge. "It was a surprise to see how little students understood basic personal finance, even when they were enrolled in an advanced business-related subject," says Cull. "I’ve seen high-achieving students let their grades slip, or not submit assignments on time. Often it would come back to a financial situation affecting their sleep and mental well-being." To bridge the gap, she considered creating a tool that offers students advice before they make financial decisions. Assisted by Professor Catherine Attard in the School of Education, she partnered with UniBank — a bank focused on serving the university sector — and a developer from Western’s Launch Pad startup incubator, to design a personal finance app specifically for university students in Australia, called Wallet$mart. The app includes features and resources covering seven crucial areas for student life: borrowing, budgeting, buying a car, education fees, employment, moving out of home, and saving. When they sign up, students are tested on their knowledge of personal finance. This generates a 'Wallet$mart score' that students are encouraged to improve upon as they learn from in-app resources. In a survey conducted after five months of app use, Cull found that 75% of the students using it felt it had positively influenced their financial knowledge and money management habits. Students who used all features of the app answered 81% more accurately on questions commonly used to test basic financial literacy than students who weren’t using the app. From: 1:00pm Wednesday, October 22, 2025 To: 2:00pm Wednesday, October 22, 2025 Location: Parramatta City Campus Campus: Parramatta City Audiences: Academics & researchers, General Interest, Post-graduate students, Undergraduate Students Categories: Community Events, Thought Leadership Events Registration: Registration is required for this event. A Storybook of Culling - Associate Professor David R. Cole The year is 2095, the devastating effects of climate change persist despite global efforts to mitigate their impact. Set in the Persianized city of Sal’lad, this tale explores the collision of two disparate narrative within the same tumultuous backdrop. An academic finds himself ensnared in a perilous liaison with a captivating Persian woman, while behind the scenes, a clandestine society orchestrates what they believe to be the greatest act in human history. As the twenty-first century lurches from crisis to crisis, humanity remains mired in unresolved turmoil. Unbeknownst to the world, a secret society devises a solution to the planet’s woes. Yet, their plans are shrouded in mystery, guarded by the threat of death for any who dare to speak of them. Navigating the treacherous landscape of impending catastrophe and lost love, only the innocence of a child-like consciousness may comprehend the precipice navigate the precipice of these singularly horrific acts. This is a Storybook of Culling – a tale of heartbreak and the chilling rationalization of acts too unspeakable to fathom. David R. Cole is an Associate Professor in Education and Cultural Analysis at Western Sydney University. He has lived in Egypt, South America and Australia. In the 1990s, he was at the University of Warwick, UK, and studied theory-fiction alongside the Cybernetic Culture Research Unit (CCRU). He has previously published two works in this genre, A Mushroom of Glass and The Nook in the Stream. He has been working in teacher education in Australia since 2004, and during that time has published 18 academic books that have helped to define the knowledge field of Deleuze and Education. He believes that creativity and imaginative thought are under threat in contemporary society, and their renewal is the key to humanity’s future survival.
